content.problemStatement:
In C++, **public access modifier** allows class members (fields and methods) to be **accessible from anywhere** in the program. Members declared as public can be accessed directly by any other class or function. This is the most permissive access level in C++.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
class ClassName {
public:
    dataType variableName;  // public variable
    returnType methodName(); // public method
};
```

---

**Example:**
```cpp
#include  
using namespace std; 

class Demo {
public:  // Public access modifier: Members are accessible outside the class
    int x;  // Public variable: Can be accessed directly by objects of the class

    // Public method: Displays the value of 'x'
    void display() {
        cout << "Public variable x: " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() { // Main function: Entry point of the program
    Demo obj;  // Create an object of class Demo

    obj.x = 10;  // Assign a value to public variable 'x' (direct access allowed)
    obj.display(); // Call the public method to display the value of 'x'

    return 0; 
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```default
Public variable x: 10
```

